05146nam a22006855i 9781487579715DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20201989onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875797157 a10.3138/97814875797152doi  a(DE-B1597)549351  a(OCoLC)1153537108  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aDA1b.M46 1989 7aHIS0150002bisacsh04a941.052201 aMendyk, Stan A. E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10a'Speculum Britanniae' :b'Regional Study, Antiquarianism, and Science in Britain to 1700 /cStan A. E. Mendyk. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©1989  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tCHAPTER ONE. Introduction: 'Where the Choir Was ...' -- tCHAPTER TWO. 'A Hole Worlde of Thinges Very Memorable' -- tCHAPTER THREE. Speculum Britanniae -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Removing the 'Eclipse from the Sunne' -- tCHAPTER FIVE. 'Rapidly Thinning Wisps and Patches' -- tCHAPTER SIX. 'Men Wake As from Deep Sleep' -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Metamorphosis -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. 'To Serve the Commonwealth of Learning' -- tCHAPTER NINE. 'This Secret Call' -- tCHAPTER TEN. Remedying 'Chief Defects' -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN. 'Learning So Much Neglected' -- tCHAPTER TWELVE. 'Industrious Searchers into the History of Nature' -- tCHAPTER THIRTEEN. Conclusion: 'Rust of Old Monuments' -- tNOTES -- tSELECT BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLocal history has been studied in Britain for at least 500 years. In this comprehensive study Stan Mendyk examines many of the first county and regional histories compiled in Britain (focusing especially on England) up to about 1700. Mendyk considers first the precedent set by the ancients, such as Strabo and Ptolemy, in firmly establishing chronographical (i.e., topographical-historical) investigation, and then within that framework explores the work of a number of British historians: Bede, Gildas, William of Worcester, John Leland, William Camden, and William Lambarde. He offers summaries of the contents of their works, an identification of the authors and their connections with one another, and explanations of the means used to collect information. He notes trends within the works, such as the infusion of a patriotic element into history and they role of insularity in shaping them. Placing these works in a broader context, Mendyk discusses some of the changes in the study of history during this period and assesses their impact on local historiography: the conflict between ancients and moderns, the development of natural history and geo-history as fields of study, and the overall development of natural history and geo-history as fields of study, and the overall development of historiography in the Tudor-Stuart period. Political and social upheaval each play a part, as do a number of other factors: the voyages of discovery, the work of Sir Francis Bacon and the Royal Society in promoting the new science, and the continuing interest in such non-scientific endeavours as alchemy and astrology. Mendyk presents an approach that integrates history, geography, historiography, and science to expand the boundaries of conventional interpretations of local history, and in so doing illuminates a remarkable body of early work in the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAntiquarianszGreat Britain. 0aSciencezGreat BritainxHistoryy16th century. 0aSciencezGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z9783110490